Homework # 3 - Solution

Question 1

Part A

The clearest way is to write your own function first to deal with a single vector (column of iris), and then apply this function to each column using lapply()

myFUN <- function(column) {
  if(is.numeric(column)) {
    shapiro.test(column)
  }
}

iris_results <- lapply(iris, myFUN)
iris_results

Part B

This time, I write my own function, but I do it right on the same line (an inline function). It is a little harder to read, but not too bad in this simple case.

pvals <- lapply(iris_results, FUN= function(result) {return(result$p.value)})
pvals
## $Sepal.Length
## [1] 0.01018116
## 
## $Sepal.Width
## [1] 0.1011543
## 
## $Petal.Length
## [1] 7.412263e-10
## 
## $Petal.Width
## [1] 1.680465e-08
## 
## $Species
## NULL

Alternatively, I could write the function first and then do lapply, so this is the same.

getPval <- function(theList) {
  return(theList$p.value)
}

pvals <- lapply(iris_results, FUN=getPval)
pvals
## $Sepal.Length
## [1] 0.01018116
## 
## $Sepal.Width
## [1] 0.1011543
## 
## $Petal.Length
## [1] 7.412263e-10
## 
## $Petal.Width
## [1] 1.680465e-08
## 
## $Species
## NULL

Part D

mean(iris$Sepal.Length^2)
## [1] 34.82567
median(iris$Sepal.Length^2)
## [1] 33.64

Part E

These values are different because the distribution of iris$Sepal.Length^2 is asymmetric, as shown in the below histogram.

qplot(iris$Sepal.Length^2)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

The distribution has a long right tail, which heavily influences the mean, pulling it towards the larger values. The median is less affected by extreme values.

Question 2

Part A

body.sizes <- rnorm(1000, mean=10, sd=3)
## make a copy so we can always go back
body.sizes.original <- body.sizes

Part B

for(year in 1:10) {
  body.sizes <- body.sizes * 1.15
}

#save the results
body.sizes.growth <- body.sizes

Part C

growth.rates <- rnorm(1000, 1.15, 0.2)

#reset the body.sizes variable
body.sizes <- body.sizes.original

for(year in 1:10) {
  body.sizes <- body.sizes * growth.rates
}

body.sizes.vargrowth <- body.sizes

Part D

#reset the body.sizes variable
body.sizes <- body.sizes.original

for(year in 1:10) {
  body.sizes <- body.sizes * growth.rates * rnorm(1, mean=1, sd=0.2)
}

body.sizes.environmentalgrowth <- body.sizes

Part E

Note: I made histograms too because I like them, but I didn’t ask you to.

With variable growth rates

Part F

  1. Does growth of a normally-distributed population lead to non-normal distributions? No
    1. Does variation in growth cause non-normality? Yes
    2. Does environmental stochasticity reduce or amplify body size variation? It aplifies it…check out their standard deviations
